column169: Drivers are required to perform a walk around before moving the truck. This individual driver failed to perform his walk around. Drivers need to have the policies put in place for safety retrained and enforced routinely to ensure drivers perform all tasks required of them.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Driver reported a 20-25 gallon spill at consignee BP Husky Refining in Oregon OH.  He had been pumping for about 45 minutes when the hose attached to the pump outlet developed a 5” split in it about 5” from the connector.  Driver was on the other side of the trailer with the plant rep checking sight gauge when he heard the noise.  He immediately ran around and shut down.  The spill went in a containment area with a drain to their waste water system.  They hosed the area down.  The driver said that they were getting their spill team out     He said the one that burst was new in October when he got his new truck.  He said it looked okay when he hooked it up.   Chemtrec report #20150601-00104.
column169: We have very few hose failures happen.  Most often we find that hoses split or rupture, especially between 3-10" from the end of thse hose,  due to tankwash facilities sticking hose cleaning wands inside the hose to clean it out.  The ends of the wands are sharp, pressurized, and rub directly on the hose lining.  Due to the fact that not all hoses are used on every load it makes it very difficult to trace back the guilty tankwash party.  However our tankwash director is mentioning this on his weekly tankwash call so that they implement hose blocks/restrictors from going into the hoses or another process to avoid this from happening.  We are also reviewing with the driver to ensure he looks inside the end of each hose very closely.  Although its not easy to see in the hose very far.

A caller stated that his wife and son were traveling by our tractor / trailer and product was coming off of the trailer and they had their windows down.  He stated that they got some on their skin and some in the mouth.  I asked if they had any water or berage on site that they could use to rinse their mouths out (careful not to swallow) and rinse their skin.  He stated they did not.  I promptly emailed him the SDS and advised against having them drive after being exposed to a chemical and to have them call 911.  In the interests of time and safety for his family I asked him to hang up and get 911 dispatched and to call me back so we could get the next pieces in motion.      The caller was not on site with his family.  I will note that he seemed unusually calm and patient during the phone call when there was an unknown product on his family.  He never did call back in but our accident department reached out to them via the email address I sent the SDS over to.  They did respond back today that they are claiming to have respiratory issues.  We’re not sure yet the extent of the medical issues and whether any medical treatment was obtained that day at my recommendation.      When the incident occurred I reached out to the driver immediately following the conversation with the initial caller.  I was able to confirm that he was pulled over dealing with it and that it was a washout cap that had come off.  He was less than 2 miles from the shipper.  Nothing was on the ground but there was product on the side of his trailer.  He secured a new washout cap on the trailer and headed back to the tankwash to have the exterior cleaned off.
column169: The action taken was that we let the driver go.  He stated that when he pre-tripped the trailer the cap seemed flush when really it must have been cross-threaded.  We had the driver on video going through his pre-trip.  He did not check the washout caps on his inspection as originally stated and is an important step that we preach heavily.  I believe this was an isolated incident and the actions taken were appropriate given the circumstances.  We will continue to train on washout cap inspection in our yearly training events using this incident as a training tool.

column168: The Limited Quantity DG and other aircraft parts were loaded in a stores mtx van by stores clerk A to prepare this for delivery to the aircraft gate side. column168: Let me preface this by stating that after the driver was in the plant safety shower they took him to the hospital as a precaution.  They treated and released him which i don't believe counts as being admitted to the hospital so my entry on that part of the form shows a '0' for hospitalizations.      The customers hose hook up was a PVC hook up suspended 5 feet in the air.  He was using 15psi or less as he unloaded into the customer tank.  The trailer went empty and the PVC fill line started to shake (as expected as air started to come through the line).  The driver shut the valves down on our trailer.  He then opened the internal valve and the external valve about 1/4 of the way (to keep the air controlled) while he walked and cleared the lines to the customer shut off valve.  As he was walking the line the customers PVC piping snapped off and a pint of product vaporized into a mist that sprayed the driver.  Product got on his chemical suit and on his face under his face shield and into his eyes.  We require Chemical goggles, chemical suit, chemical gloves, goggles, and face shield. Driver was wearing safety glasses instead of goggles.  This is how the mist entered his eyes.  He was taken to a safety shower and then taken to the hospital as a precautionary measure.  Driver was given the all clear by the hospital to drive and the next day he is feeling fine (thankfully).  At this time we don't believe the amount of air pressure used or the processes he followed led to the snapped fill line.  We believe that the fill line was either old and deteriorated or is not in a best design capacity.
column169: Our driver could have prevented this injury by using the proper protective gear.  In interviewing the driver it sounds as though he did not know where to look in his electronic work assignment for the correct PPE and thought that the safety glasses with side shields along with the face shield should be enough to protect him in the event of an incident.  He understands that was a bad decision and is going to spend time with our training team to ensure he understands PPE and where to find what should be used.      On the customer's fill line, our customer (shipper) is working with the consignee to determine what (if any) design changes need to be implemented.

column168: LION OIL TRANSPORTATION DRIVER WAS MAKING A 87 OCTANE FUEL DELIVERY TO A CONVENIENCE STORE AT 1700 HWY 34 S TERRELL, TX. THE DISPATCHED GALLONS WERE 6,500 GALS WHICH WAS UNDER THE ULLAGE READINGS PROVIDED BY THE STORE VEEDER SYSTEM. THE VEEDER ROOT SYSTEM IN THE STORE WAS NOT WORKING PROPERLY WHICH GAVE INCORRECT READINGS. THE TANK IN THE GROUND WAS NOT VENTING PROPERLY AS WELL AND BECAME PRESSURIZED. THE FUEL WAS FORCED BACK INTO THE TRAILER AND RELEASED OUT OF THE SECONDARY VAPOR CONNECTION. APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS WAS RELEASED ONTO THE CONCRETE BEFORE THE FLOW WOULD CEASE. NO SOIL OR WATERWAY WAS CONTAMINATED. TAS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE WAS CALLED AND REPORTED WITHIN AN HOUR FOR A COMPLETE CLEAN UP. A REPORT WAS ALSO MADE WITH TDEQ NUMBER 215423.
column169: GALLONS WILL BE VERIFIED WHEN THE VEEDER ROOT IS NOT WORKING PROPERLY.  THE STORE WAS NOTIFIED AND MAINTENANCE WAS SENT FOR REPAIR.

column168: At 1:55 hrs on 6/6/15, a Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) employee reported smelling an odor sourcing from UTLX 900787 in the KCSR Port Arthur Yard. A response contractor was dispatched to the yard to investigate. A small leak sourcing from the pressure relief device (PRD) was detected. The release was caused from the tank car being overloaded with pressure (this car was found with 66 psi). Car is equipped with a 75 psi PRV which by specification are only vapor tight below 60 psi.  Ideally, these tank cars should not be offered into transportation with pressures exceeding 60 psi. Other industry subject matter experts indicate that 35-40 psi is their maximum. The PRV is not defective and was sealed with minor modulation of the retainer cap. A Midland kit was installed over the pressure relief device to assure the vapor tight seal.      File Note: Item 25(1) did not have a selection for human error failure, over pressurization, or any other choice that would fit this situation. The DOT parameters require a selection for this question. An arbitrary selection of "Basic Material" was picked to process this report. However, this package did not have a defect, and the release was caused from human error of over pressurization.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Shipper, please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Tank car GATX 79948 was in the railyard and reported leaking commodity from the protective housing on its side shell.  Minimal ground impact from spillage was observed.  BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected GATX 79948 reported the leak had stopped upon inspection, but could not identify where the leak was coming from.  BNSF contract responder was called to inspect the car and pressure the car with nitrogen to determine the leak source.  It was determined the liquid valve flange was not properly tightened at the flange to the pressure plate.  All four flange bolt nuts on the liquid valve flange fitting were properly tightened approximately  turn.  The responders tool tightened the flange bolt nuts and secured the car.  The released commodity had evaporated from the shell and ground upon the contract responders arrival.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical tightness of all valves and fittings.

column168: This was the result of improper packaging for transportation. One ounce of the product spilled and was cleaned up by the terminal staff and transferred into a 5 gallon drum for OS and D. The spill contacted the trailer floor and spilled from the lid of the container. It was an immediate release.

A 550 pound supersac bag fell over during transit and released 5 pounds of solid methoxy nitro venzenamine UN2811. The product was released in the trailer and Contractors were responded. The bags appeared to have been punctured and the product spilled out. 2 drums of debris were generated and the site was cleaned up.

During the unloading process, the transfer hose ruptured near the consignee's connection point.  The size of the rupture was about 3 inches on the outer cover and about 1 inch on the inner lining of the hose.  The delivery driver immediately shut valves and stopped the transfer of product through the ruptured hose.  The reported estimate of spillage was approximately 3 liquid gallons.    Due to on-going construction at the consignee's facility, the hose connection required a bend in the hose of near 90 degrees creating a small crease.  It is believed that this weakened the hose causing the rupture.
column169: A 90 degree fitting has been assembled for use on deliveries to this location.  This will stop the potential for "creasing" the hose and possibly causing a weak spot in the transfer hose.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On June 11, 2015 at 03:10 hours personnel in the CSX Big Four Yard discovered GATX 61166, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, venting from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Arkema, was notified (CHEMTREC Report #2015-0611-00041). Quick Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disc in the non-reclosing pressure relief device had ruptured.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative Shane Adams (270-395-6644).  Contractor personnel installed a new frangible disc. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. No special move was required.  No QA7.1 filed.     NARRI: 2(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40  Cause Code: 1004

column58: Liquid Line; Manway or Dome Cover
column168: On 06/15/15 at 1446 hours CSXT yard personnel at the Boyles Yard terminal located at 2800 Seaboard Road Birmingham, AL discovered DBUX300768, a loaded tank car of Ethanol, leaking from the liquid line valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, MGPI OF INDIANA LLC, was notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line valve leaking product and partially open and not secured.  Hepaco also discovered that the manway gasket was cracked. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Matthew Collins, 913-360-0505). Contractor personnel closed the liquid line and replaced the manway gasket. The leak was secured and the car released. This incident did not require a special switching move. column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On June 18, 2015, at 15:01 hours, FRA Hazardous Material Inspector at the CSXT Hawthorne Yard, Indianapolis, Indiana took exception to SHPX 208012, a loaded tank car of UN1268, Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S . Reportedly, there was hissing from the vacuum relief valve (VRV). The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Heritage Crystal Clean LLC, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2015-06-18-00263 . Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Hawthorne Yard. Summit placed a slight nitrogen blanket and found that the VRV was in fact releasing product. The VRV was removed and a plug was installed for a temporary repair. The shipper representative, Joe Licari 312-898-1983 was notified of the situation found. Heritage applied for One Time Movement Approval and will have a qualified repair facility replace the VRV and re-qualify the tank car. This incident did require a special move  . column168: VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING ON I-15 NORTHBOUND AT APPROXIMATELY 500 SOUTH. DUE TO FAILURE OF WELD IN VOID AREA BETWEEN BULKHEADS WHICH SEPARATES COMPARTMENT ONE AND COMPARTMENT TWO OF SEMI TRAILER, THE TRAILER BUCKLED IN THE CORNER BETWEEN BULKHEADS. DRIVER MAINTAINED CONTROL OF VEHICLE AND WAS ABLE TO PULL INTO EMERGENCY LANE. NEITHER COMPARTMENT HOLDING THE CRUDE OIL RUPTURED AND THE ONLY OIL THAT WAS PSILLED WAS OIL FROM MANIFOLD (APPROX. 10 GAL). NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED. OIL WAS PUMPED OFF FROM COMPARTMENT ONE AND TWO ONTO ANOTHER FORELAND TRAILER AND DELIVERED.
column169: There are currently no regulations in place to test the void area between the bulkheads of cargo tanks. We are implementing a procedure to test void area between the bulkheads by applying a pressure at 1 -1.5 lbs. for a 5 minute period to make sure the void area can maintain pressure. If void area can not maintain pressure, we would further investigate by removing insulation from cargo tank to perform a visual inspection in order to identify why pressure could not be maintained.

On 6/10/2015, a railcar freight trailer was unloading a shipment of UN1903 Iodine along with other chemicals when the driver noticed a leak coming from inside the trailer. A contractor was sent to the site and removed all 24 pallets of contaminated drums with a forklift. The end result was finding one leaking 55 gallon steel drum near the front of the trailer. It appears to have been punctured due to a forklift during loading. All of it's contents were spilled during transit on the railcar. Clean up was done and the leaking drum was overpacked into a new drum.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: This incident pertains to an approximate 1/2 gallon release of UN3105 Organic Peroxide Type D Liquid (Methyl Ethyl Ketone Peroxide). The material released from (1) 5-gallon pail as the result of a load shift during transit.  The pail was damaged as the result of the shift. The contractor that was dispatched concluded it was punctured by a unidentifiable object. The free liquid on the trailer floor was cleaned and the terminal was advised to let it air out overnight before using again. (1) 55-gallon drum of hazardous waste containing the impacted absorbents, damaged pail, and a contaminated pallet was generated for pending disposal and taken with the contractor.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On 6/29, a dock worker noticed a shipment of UN1294 Toluene leaking on the dock cement. Contractors were dispatched and reported 3 ounces of product leaking from 1 one-gallon metal can. The leak appeared to be the result of a puncture during shipping or unloading operations. The pallet was also contaminated so contractors replaced the pallet and overpacked the damaged container into a 10 gallon steel drum.

On June 21, 2015, at 12:34 hours, a Trainmaster at the CSXT Avon Terminal, Avon, Indiana reported an odor in the vicinity of GATX 2091, a loaded tank car of UN3289, Toxic Liquid, Corrosive, Inorganic, N.O.S. (SODIUM SULFIDE SOLUTION). Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Hawthorne Yard and discovered that odor was being emitted from the vacuum relief valve (VRV). The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Heritage Crystal Clean LLC, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2015-06-21-00049. Summit inspected the (VRV) and discovered foreign material around the gaskets that appeared to be saw dust. The (VRV) was cleaned and then tested and found to be seating properly. The shipper representative, Paul Kohlhoff 224-239-0680 was notified of the situation found. Heritage applied for One Time Movement Approval and will have a qualified repair facility re-inspect the (VRV) and determine the origin of the foreign material. This incident did require a special move    NARRI: 5x(5+5+1)x(2+0) = 110  Cause code:1033

column168: This incident consists of a release of 1oz of UN1993 Unisol Liquid Red BK-50 leaked from the release valve on top of a metal tote. The release has only impacted the body of the tote. The contractor that was dispatched wiped down the small leak on the side of the tote and will removed the cap to inspect the gasket. Contractor called back to report that the bung was loose from the shipper, but was replaced. The container has been decontaminated and waste has been contained to (1) 5-gallon bucket.

This incident pertains to a 2 box release of amount of UN0336 FIREWORKS in the rear of a trailer. The contractor that was dispatched for this incident mentioned that the material the boxes are made of is of poor quality. 2 loosely shipped boxes experienced releases of product onto the trailer floor. The loose and damaged boxes were re-secured and re-taped. All the loose materials were re-boxed and re-taped. The contractor stated that there was no black powder or any of the internal components of any of the freight released. No wastes were generated from this incident

column168: In the Barstow, CA trainyard FRA Hazmat inspectors performed an audit and found the UTLX 211965 with wetness from the combination housing on the top of the car.  BNSF Hazmat responders investigated and found the liquid valve to be closed, but product had bypassed the valve.  In addition, the secondary closure plug was found only threaded on by a couple of threads and was moveable by hand allowing the product to release.  Valve was inspected and re-closed, and pipe plug was properly applied and tool tight.  Approximately 1 gallon released and was confined to the top of the car.  The product quickly evaporated so no cleanup process was initiated.  Suspect a defect with the valve's sealing surface to be determined by a certified tank car repair facility.
column169: Product shipper should review pre-trip inspection process with employees and perform quality audits to ensure non-accidental release will not occur while in transportation.  Shipper was instructed to file for OTMA prior to any further movement of the car.

column168: On June 10, 2015 at approximately 10:00 am PDT the TRFX 1407 loaded with petroleum crude oil STCC 4910191 was found leaking in the BNSF railyard in Vancouver,WA. The leak was found by BNSF trainyard employees who reported wetness down both sides of the tank in the area of the manway nozzle. The car was routed to the repair track and after further investigation it was found to have all of the manway swing bolts loose and/or less than tool tight.  BNSF contractor NRC Environmental Services responded and inspected the manway nozzle gasket and found no defects.  Contractor properly torqued all manway bolts and wiped down the surface of the tank car.  It was estimated that 1 gallon of liquid was lost during this release.
column169: Shipper should review loading processes, securement standards, and pre-trip inspection process with all applicable employees and audit periodically for compliance.

column168: June 4th 2040 hours: SUNPRO received a request to respond to leaking railcars CBTX 742130 in Smithboro, Illinois. SUNPRO dispatched a response team, which consisted of one (1) project manager and one (1) environmental technician.    2300 hours: The response team mobilized in one (1) fully-stocked service vehicle.    June 5, 2015    0300 hours: SUNPRO arrived on site and met with the Trainmaster, who guided the response team to crude oil railcar CBTX 742130. SUNPRO held a safety meeting, where the Health and Safety Plan (HASP) was reviewed and signed. The Trainmaster placed SUNPRO on standby while track protection was secured.    0900 hours: The response team scaled railcar CBTX 742130 and removed seals FRA #40911 and Allied #0945897 from the utility housing. The project manager inspected the railcars VRV and noted that it was leaking vapors.    0915 hours: SUNPRO utilized a degreasing agent and hand tools to re-seat the VRV. The project manager noted that the vapor leak ceased. SUNPRO sealed the utility housing shut with seal #361865.    2040 hours: SUNPRO received a request to respond to leaking railcar CBTX 742770 in Smithboro, Illinois. SUNPRO dispatched a response team, which consisted of one (1) project manager and one (1) environmental technician.    2300 hours: The response team mobilized in one (1) fully-stocked service vehicle.    June 5, 2015    0300 hours: SUNPRO arrived on site and met with the Trainmaster, who guided the response team to crude oil railcars CBTX 742770. SUNPRO held a safety meeting. The Trainmaster placed SUNPRO on standby while track protection was secured.    0820 hours: The Trainmaster secured track protection and cleared SUNPRO to begin operations. The response team scaled railcar CBTX 742770 and removed seals FRA #40920 and Allied #0945899 from the utility housing. The project manager opened the utility housing and noted that the vapor relief valve (VRV) was leaking.    0830 hours: SUNPRO attempted to remove the leaking valve but could not due to limited space. The response team utilized a degreasing agent and hand tools to re-seat the VRV. The project manager noted that the vapor leak ceased. SUNPRO sealed the utility housing shut with seal #361862.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 2 gallons of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. The material in the drum was pH'd.  The pH was neutral.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. If a possible safety or comnpliance issue is identified, drivers are instructed to contact a manager or supervisor.  IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

On June 30th, 2015 at 1016 hours personnel from ODFJELL industries discovered SHPX 203213, a loaded tank car of Ethylene Glycol leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Tracy Shroeder (ODFELL), Operator Davis South Carolina DHEC, Brent T, National Response Center were notified. HMS Manager Rob James, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found that the car was over loaded with product. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Tracy Schroeder Phone number 832-284-3615. The car was shoved back into the ODFJELL who loaded the car so that product could be off loaded. This incident did require a special switching move.    NAR Cause Code:  200 - Manway, Hinged + Bolted    5 (5+1+0)  x  (2+0) = 60

column168: On 6/30, a trailer carrying UN1789 muriatic acid reported a strong odor in the back of the trailer. Contractors arrived and removed the packages to find a leaking 1 gallon plastic can of muriatic acid. It appears that a load shipment of 22 - 1 gallon cans was crushed due to a double stacked pallet. 8 ounces of the product from 1 can spilled onto other containers in the shipment. The release was immediate and was contained to the trailer and adjacent freight. No soil or waterways were impacted

column168: At approximately 10:15 a.m. on June 15, 2015, facility employees discovered a liquid spill beneath trailers at the facility dock. The discovery was made while conducting a facility inspection.  The spill was reported to the National Response Center (“NRC”) at 11:54 am on June 15, 2015. It was reported to the North Carolina Department Environment and Natural Resources (“NCDENR”) after reporting to the NRC.  Reporting to the Mecklenburg County LEPC was not required as the spill was contained on the facility site. The spill was immediately contained at the time of discovery and no additional material was spilled.  An emergency response contractor was mobilized to the facility on June 15, 2015 to initiate response efforts.    Approximately 1,040 liters of waste chromic acid and sulfuric acid mixture that was manifested as characteristically hazardous waste was spilled onto an asphalt and concrete parking area:    • D001 Oxidizer as described at 40 CFR 261.21(a)(4)  • D002 as described at §261.22(a)(1)  • D007 as described at §261.24(a) and (b)    The waste was approved for receipt at Heritage Environmental Services, LLC in Indianapolis, Indiana, a RCRA permitted treatment storage and disposal facility, for management on waste stream 10156-51 (Attachment 1).  The waste chromic acid was generated by Apex Tool Group, LLC located in Apex, North Carolina.  Two Intermediate Bulk Containers (IBC’S) of the waste  were being transported on page 1, line 4, of Uniform Hazardous Waste Manifest number 000678000WAS from Apex Tool Group, LLC in Apex, NC to Heritage Environmental Services, LLC in Indianapolis, IN (Attachment 2).  The spill notification and subsequent response was initiated as a result of a packaging failure of one of the IBCs.  The waste present in the IBC containers appeared to be incompatible with the materials of construction (HDPE).  The container was located on a Heritage Transport, LLC 53-foot van trailer at the Ten Day Transfer facility when it failed.    The area affected was central to the facility with the nearest pathway off property being a storm drain that was bermed and covered immediately upon discovery.  The spill did not reach the storm drain. There was no precipitation the day of the spill or during the clean up efforts.    The liquid remaining from the two IBCs containing the same wastestream was transferred into seven (7) 55-gallon high-density polyethylene (“HDPE”) containers with 2.0mil Teflon PFA film inner liners.  The containers were then placed within HDPE over-packs. The material was returned to the generator on a Uniform Hazardous Waste Manifest (Attachment 3) on June 19, 2015.     Clay absorbent material was applied to the spill to solidify.  This was swept and shoveled into containers. Acid Gator absorbent for acid spill absorption was then applied to the stained areas along with a bicarbonate solution. The Acid Gator was then broomed in and shoveled into containers.  After neutralizing and absorbing the spill materials

column168: On 6/11/2015, a trailer at a truck terminal reported a release of 3 gallons of UN2582 from a 275 gallon tote. The spill immediately impacted the dock floor as it was being unloaded. A contractor was sent to transfer the damaged tote to a new tote and clean up the spill using absorbents and a neutralizer. The contaminated PPE and absorbents were placed into a 55 gallon poly drum and taken for disposal.

column168: DRIVER WAS ENROUTE BACK TO MIDLAND SITE FROM A SHOT LOCATION IN THE NAZARETH, TEXAS AREA. HE WAS SOUTHBOUND ON STATE HIGHWAY 137, 19.6 MILES NORTH OF STANTON, TX. HE LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AS HE PASSED ON OIL FIELD LOADING STATION AND COMING OUT OF A CURVE. HE OVER REACTED AND ATTEMPTED TO REGAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE BY TURNING TO THE LEFT TO KEEP IT ON THE ROADWAY. THE REAR WHEELS BROKE TRACTION CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO LOSE CONTROL FURTHER AND THEN BEGAN TO SLIDE SIDEWAYS. HE THEN LEFT THE ROADWAY AT THE ENTRANCE TO A CRUDE OIL LOADING FACILITY AND TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 60 TO 70 FEET AS THE VEHICLE BEGAN TO ROLL ON ITS RIGHT SIDE. THE VEHICLE CONTINUED ON ITS SIDE TURNING AROUND AND STOPPED FACING NORTH ON THE NORTHBOUND SHOULDER. DURING THE ROLLOVER EVENT APPROXIMATELY 15 TO 20 LBS OF AMMONIUM NITRATE IN PRILL FORM WAS RELEASED FROM THE VEHICLE ONTO THE ROADWAY.  THE SPILL DID NOT CAUSE ANY ENVIRONMENTAL PROBLEMS. CLEANUP WAS CONDUCTED BY BUCKLEY POWDER.
column169: RETRAINING WILL BE CONDUCTED WITH THE DRIVER AND ALL EMPLOYEES AT ALL SITES IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE US DOT PHMSA SPECIAL PERMIT 11579 RETRAINING PROGRAM. THIS WILL INCLUDE ROLLOVER TRAINING AWARENESS, DOT VEHICLE OFF ROAD RECOVERY, DOT SPECIAL PERMIT, DRIVING DROWSY, AND BPC PROFESSINAL DRIVER.

During a routine walk through inspection at the Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. in-transit storage facility at Des Moines, IA a leaking drum was discovered in a trailer unit. The drum was discovered to have a pin hole leak at the side wall resulting in a release of approximately 0.5 cups of material. Facility management was notified and an in house crew responded. The response crew donned the proper PPE, over-packed the damaged drum and clean up debris into a suitable salvage drum, and secured the drum for continued transportation to the intended disposal facility. The Iowa Department of Natural resources was notified. Duty operator Gross provided report # 062315-wcg-1719.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. The shipper was advised of the incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity. The driver was re-instructed to perform a thorough inspection of all containers prior to accepting them for transportation. The shipper advised of a change in their process that may have resulted in a change of constituents in the waste disposal profile. The change in constituents resulted in corrosion of the steel drum. Clean Harbors has frozen the disposal profile for review and all future shipments will be placed in poly drums.

column168: THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION:  * WAS SORTED TO BOX-LINE #2 AND PLACED INTO THE RESPECTIVE CAGE READY TO BE PLACED AND SORTING INTO THE DESIGNATED PACKAGE CAR.  * A PRE-LOADER WENT TO PICK UP THE PACKAGE FROM THE CAGE AND NOTICED SMOKE WAS PRESENT; HOWEVER HE DID NOT KNOW WHICH PACKAGE IN THE CAGE WAS ACTUALLY SMOKING  * A RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO INVESTIGATE WHERE THE SMOKE WAS COMING FROM AND THE (RMP-SPENCER DAY) CAME WITH HIM  * SPENCER DAY AND DONNY STARTED TAKING PACKAGES OUT OF THE CAGE TO DETERMINE WHICH PACKAGE WAS SMOKING!  AFTER TAKING A FEW PACKAGES OUT, SPENCER REMOVED THE SMOKING PACKAGE AND THREW PACKAGE TO THE GROUND WHEN HE REALIZED IT WAS THE ONE SMOKING.  * SPENCER USED THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO PUT THE FIRE OUT.  * THE BATTERY CHARGER WAS IN THE BOX AND IT LOOKED LIKE THE TAG WIRE TOGETHER WITH THE PAPER CLIP HOLDING THE CHARGER INFORMATION CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE POSITIVE CHARGE SIDE OF THE CHARGER AND CREATED A SPARK WHICH STARTING THE FIRE.  * THE CORNER OF THE PACKAGE WAS BURNT AND THE CHARGER INSIDE THE BOX DID NOT LOOK DAMAGED.
column169: RECOMMEND TALKING TO CUSTOMER/SHIPPER ABOUT COVERING THE END CLIPS OF THE NEGATIVE AND POSITIVE POLES OF CHARGERS TO PREVENT ANY CONDUCTORS FROM TOUCHING CHARGES AND CAUSING SPARKS AND FIRES.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE IN THE UNLOAD. WHEN I ARRIVED I NOTICED THE PACKAGE HAD A DIAMOND CORROSIVE LABEL. MY DECISION TREE INSTRUCTED ME TO WEAR GOGGLES, BOOTS, APRON, AND GLOVES USING SILVER INNER SHIELD LINER. I TORE OFF 5 INCHES OF PH TAPE AND IMMERSED IN LIQUID. THE SPILL LIQUID WAS AN ALKALINE AND WHEN I APPLIED THE SODIUM BICARBONATE, THERE WAS NO FIZZING REACTION. I REAPPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE AND RETEST UNTIL THE SPILL LIQUID WAS NEUTRALIZED. I MIX APPROVED UNIVERSAL ABSORBENT TO THE SPILL MATERIAL TO COMPLETELY ABSORB ALL THE SPILL LIQUID. ONCE I DID A THOROUGH CLEANUP OF THE SPILL I PLACED THE PACKAGE AND ABSORBED MATERIAL INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY AND TRANSPORTED IT TO THE DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column168: Tank AMLU885992 was seen leaking from the its bottom valve first thing in the morning 6/12/2015. The tank was carrying ferric chloride. It had leaked about 50 gallons before it was discovered. The product must have eaten through the valve and started to leak earlier that morning. Its hard to tell what caused the leak, because the tank had not been moved for 3 days. After initial containing the spill, it was determined that the valve was not able to fixed to stop the leak. The tank was placed into a plastic containment tarp to stop any further spill on to the pier. BEI was brought in to help transfer the product into an empty container that last contained ferric chloride. Penco was brought in to assist with clean up.
column169: The spills is still under investigation so preventive measures have not been determined yet. We do plan on additional training for spill containment.

column168: Upon arrival at the destination terminal, a pail was found damaged inside the trailer. Investigation revealed that the weight on top of the pails had caused one pail to crack and release material. The damaged pail and it's contents were placed into an overpack for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This particular incident may be used in future dock meeting discussions to help promote proper freight loading techniques and to raise awareness of double stacking heavy freight.

column168: Driver overfilled customers tank due to misunderstanding as to witch tank he should unload into. There are two tanks east and west. The driver though he was suppose to unload into the east tank but it was suppose to go into the west tank. As the driver began the unloading process he noticed the tank was overfilling. He immediately shut down the unloading process. Approximately 50 gallons of caustic overflowed to secondary containment and cleaned up in house. The driver then hooked to the west tank and continued the unloading process without further incident. There were no injuries as a result of this spill.
column169: The Trucking Supervisor met with the driver to determine why the spill occurred. The investigation revealed the driver relied on verbal instructions from the customer's receiving agent on which tank to unload into. The driver failed to require the receiving agent to physically show them the correct connection point as required on the In the Interest of Safety form. The driver failed to confirm with the receiving agent the operation of the level indicator and what reading would indicate the tank was full.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: On June 12, 2015 at 2100 ET, a 30-gallon poly drum was discovered to have dropped to the trailer floor below and cracked open, due to inadequate blocking and bracing. Approximately 20 gallons released to the trailer floor and concrete apron below. A cleanup contractor was dispatched to perform the cleanup. The damaged drum was over-packed and the neutralized impacted absorbents were containerized into a seperate drum. All waste was taken by the contractor for disposal.

column168: A CTMV was rear ended by a tractor trailer unit while passing over a RR crossing resulting in puncture to the rear shell of the tanker. the incident resulted in the release of 26855 lbs out of 40,580lbs of UN3082 Phenol Formaldehyde Resin to the roadway, shoulder and water filled ditch line. The release occurred over a period of 1.5 to 2 hours. Sand was used to dike the material and mitigate impact.

column168: THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE WHEN THE PASSENGER SIDE TIRES DROPPED OF THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WAY (FRESH REPAVING AND THE BERM WAS AT LEAST 6" DROP) THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS SIDE OFF THE ROAD IN THE GRASS AND 1100 GALLONS OUT OF THE 1980 GALLON LOAD SPILLED OUT OF 3 VENT-CAPS OUT OF THE 6 TANKS (WE THEORIZE DUE TO LIQUID SERGE FROM THE ROLL OVER). THE REMAINING LOAD OF 880 WAS SUCTIONED OUT OF THE TRUCK BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY WE HIRED (ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT) AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO OUR FACILITY. THE SAME COMPANY PREPARED THE TRUCK TO BE TOWED TO THE FLEET MECHANIC AND ALSO REMOVED ALL THE CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM THE IMPACT AREA. AT THE SCENE ALL 6 TANKS WERE SLOWLY LEAKING THE HAZMAT TEAM WAS ABLE TO STOP 3 OF THE LEAKS AT THE PRESSURE RELEASE VENT CAP. IN REGARDS TO QUESTION 32 DAMAGES - THE AMOUNTS ARE IN OUR OPINION WORST CASE SCENARIOS, DUE TO THE FACT THAT REPORTS AND INVOICES WILL NOT BE AVAILABLE WITHIN THE TIME FRAME TO SUBMIT THIS REPORT.

column168: Driver arrived at customer site to pick up drum of waste paint.  Drum was located on a pallet in containment.  After inspecting the package and ensuring bolts and bungs were tight, the driver proceeded to move the drum off the pallet.  As the drum was being moved off the containment area, a small amount of liquid escaped from the gasket.  The driver immediately reset the drum to a resting position, cleaned the area and replaced the lid with an undamaged one.  It is presumed the drum sat directly in the sun for an undetermined amount of time. And considering the heat and the material contained within, the combination resulted in accelerated weaar on the gasket and ultimately resulted in failure.
column169: Company representatives spoke with the customer and informed them of the need to provide a shaded or covered area for drum storage.  As well, and prior to transporting, check the package to include gaskets, bungs, bolts, etc. so as to correct should there be a sign of damage.

column168: On June 10, 2015 at approximately 0900 hours a container SNLU 977983 was found in the San Bernardino Intermodal Hub to be leaking.  The container was moved to the containment pit for further investigation.  After opening the rear doors and removing the contents of the container a 55 gallon drum was found punctured near the bottom just above the welded ring.  The drum contained Iodine 260 Pre-mix solution, a corrosive liquid.  The drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon overpack drum.  The container was neutralized and washed along with any other materials in the shipment that were contaminated.  Load was placed into a new container for forwarding to destination.
column169: Ensure shipper adheres to proper packaging/bracing techniques per established standards and provide proper care when handling drums and pallets to prevent puncture.

column168: On Saturday June 13, 2015 two tank cars, GATX 36359 and GATX 36360 were found in the BNSF Pasco trainyard to have wetness around the manway nozzle on the top of the car.  BNSF responder investigated cars in the yard and found both with all manway cover swing bolts less than tool tight.  Manways were opened to inspect gaskets with no defects found; lids were re-secured with proper pipe wrench and torque pattern and released for delivery to destination.  An estimated one gallon released from each car and was confined to the top of the cars which were wiped dry with absorbent pads; no environmental impact.
column169: Shipper has been contacted to re-train loading employees on proper pre-trip preparation and inspection techniques to ensure proper packaging.  In addition they should periodically audit for compliance.

column168: At approximately 1600 hours on June 13, 2015 in the BNSF Barstow trainyard, the NATX 37098 was found to have wetness coming from the top of the tank car near the combination housing.  BNSF mechanical personnel investigated further and found a small amount of product leaking from the threaded nipple at the base of the liquid valve where it fastens to the pressure plate.  No other defects were discovered so the valve assembly was turned approximately 1/4 turn with a pipe wrench to achieve tool tight condition.  It was estimated that less than one gallon was lost during this incident.  The wetness was mopped up with absorbent pads and car was cleared to continue to destination.
column169: Shipper was notified of this incident and encouraged to share the findings of this inspection with their loading operation personnel as well as re-train to the DOT packaging and pre-trip inspection requirements and perform random follow up audits to ensure compliance.

column168: GROX 132063 was reported leaking by BNSF personnel on track 1204.  Upon inspection, the man way nuts/bolts were improperly secured and found to be less than tool tight.  The man way gasket was inspected and found to be intact and in good condition.  The man way nuts were secured and the exterior of the tank car was decontaminated by BNSF First Responders.
column169: Shipper to utilize existing protocol or modify existing protocol to ensure tank cars are secured at all closures prior to leaving facility.

column168: The SB Hub LARS Team was advised in-gate trailer RDWY 130874 at San Bernardino IBU. YRC Helpline was contacted for assistance; Patriot Environmental was dispatched to remediate the leak at our facility. The leak material was discovered to be ZEPHeavy Duty High Alkaline Cleaner. Two fivegallon buckets were found empty and other buckets with some loss for a total of 16 gallons of material loss. The contractor used soda ash and other cleaning material to remediate the leak. The buckets appeared to have leaked due to the triple stack method on the pallet. Compromised product was over packed and remaining product was restacked back on new pallets.
column169: Shipper shall ensure proper loading of hazardous materials protocol is followed and will need to determine if protocols may need to be modified for smaller packages due to weight and packaging.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Upon arrival, Patriot Environmental conducted an exterior inspection and noted a thick liquid slowly dripping from the container deck at the nose section. Approximately (1.5) gallons of product leaked onto the ground. The leaking material tested HAZARDOUS and was immediately cleaned from the ground and contained. An interior inspection revealed the leaking material was OVEN CLEANER (Hazardous). Two (5 gallon) pails were damaged and leaked a total of (10) gallons.     The damaged pails were discovered in the nose section, stretch wrapped and palletized in two rows and one layer in height. According to Patriot personnel, the stretch wrap failed and the pails shifted off the pallet; compromising the pails and allowing the product to leak. Methods of securement consisted of Ty Patch and an E Brace at the rear of the load. Securement had not been applied at the nose section.
column169: Proper load securement and blocking/bracing of loads must be  implemented for all loads and all quantities to ensure the product does not shift during transportation.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On June 28, 2015 at 1415 hours, personnel at CSXT Barr Yard discovered NATX 318095, a loaded UN 1268, Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. tank car to have released product from the liquid valve. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Blue Racer Midstream, LLC was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-06-28-00044. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, the Schererville, IN branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the valve was leaking between the body of the valve and the flange bolts. SUNPRO utilized hand tools to tighten the flange bolts and the valves plug. The project manager noted that the leak stopped.     A HAZMATHOLD was placed on NATX 318095 and will require a product transfer.    Cause Code: 300 at 2 points    NARRI: 5 (5 + 5 + 0) x (3 + 0) = 150

column168: Driver loaded 50% Sulfuric Acid at Brenntag in Charlotte, NC destined for Tampa, Florida. Driver pullled into the Loves truck stop in Orangeburg, SC, drove through the fuel island and parked in the truck parking area. When driver exited the truck at approx. 0515 he noticed acid leaking from under the rear of the trailer. The leak was from a 1/4 inch hole in the bottom of the tank directly under the manway and was spilling onto the pavement. Driver contacted truck stop management and 911 emergency response. The county HAZMAT team arrived and contained the spill using containers, buoys and sand to stop the acid from running into the storm drain or the dirt. The onsite Hazmat response director, made the decision to evacuate the truck stop, including a small service station and a Waffle House located next to it. SWS Environmental arrived on scene and plugged the hole in the trailer stopping the leak. The remaining product in the trailer was pumped out into a rubber lined trailer. Approx. 1630 the truck stop and Waffle House were reopened.
column169: The trailer was inspected after and it was determined that the liner had small defects that were not indentified by visual ispection. First step KC Industries Trucking has done is to stop transporting 50% Sulfuric Acid. Second all trailers that have hauled this material were taken out of service by the company and the liners were reinspected to evauate the damage if any to these trailers.

column168: THE FOLLOWING IS A DESCRIPTION OF AN OVERFILL EVENT, NOT A PACKAGE FAILURE. DURING A FIRST TIME DELIVERY TO KELLY PLATING IN CLEVELAND, OH, THE DRIVER NOTED THAT UNLOADING CONNECTION HAD TO BE SWITCHED OUT BEFORE HE COULD UNLOAD. THE UNLOADING PIPE WAS TOO CLOSE TO THE GROUND TO CONNECT THE HOSE. THE SITE MAINTENANCE SUPERVISOR RECONFIGURED THE LOADING CONNECTION BY INSTALLING AN ELBOW TO ENABLE THE DRIVER TO CONNECT TO THE TANK. THE DRIVER CONNECTED TO THE TANK AND BEGAN THE OFF-LOADING WITH THE AIR PRESSURE SET AT 15 PSI. WHEN VAPORS BEGAN ESCAPING FROM THE BUILDING WERE THE HCL TANK WAS STORED, THE DRIVER CUT THE PRESSURE BACK TO 10 PSI AND CONTINUED UNLOADING INTO THE STORAGE TANK. SOMETIME LATER THE PRODUCT HOSE BEGAN JUMPING, INDICATING THAT THE TRAILER WAS GOING EMPTY. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PTO AND WALKED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. AS HE GLANCED TO HIS LEFT HE SAW HCL COMING FROM THE CORNER OF THE BUILDING, WERE THE TANK IS STORED. HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVES AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND NOTIFIED THE CUSTOMER. THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS ESTIMATED BETWEEN 25 TO 30 GALLONS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TURNING LEFT ONTO SOUTHBOUND RESERVE ST. FROM STOCKYARD ROAD WESTBOUND.  AFTER COMPLETING HIS TURN, OTHER VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED ON RESERVE ST, COLLIDED WITH CENTER DIVIDER IN ROADWAY, COLLIDING INTO DECORATIVE TREES AND SHRUBBERY.  AT THIS POINT VEHICLE CONTINUED PAST CENTER DIVIDER AND INTO LEFT TURN LANE ON RESERVE STREET NORTH BOUND.  VEHICLE THEN ENCROACHED INTO SOUTHBOUND LANE AND COLLIDED WITH OUR COMPANY TRAILER, WHICH WAS COMPLETING TURN SOUTHBOUND ONTO RESERVE ST. FROM STOCKYARD ROAD EASTBOUND.  VEHICLE COLLIDED WITH LEFT REAR OF OUR TRAILER, MAKING CONTACT WITH LEFT SIDE PIPING OF THE UNDER CARRIAGE OF THE TRAILER. COLLISION OCCURRED IN SOUTHBOUND LANE, OTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTHBOUND. THE PIPING SYSTEM WAS FULL OF GASOLINE, APPROXIMATELY 12 GALLONS IN THE PIPING SYSTEM, DUE JUST HAVING BEEN LOADED.  DRIVER HAD JUST LEFT LOADING FACILITY. MISSOULA POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS ARRIVED ON SCENE.  DUE TO THE FUEL SPILL AND POTENTIAL OF FIRE RISK, THE ROADWAY WAS CLOSED TEMPORARILY, FOR LESS THAN ONE HOUR. MISSOULA POLICE ARRESTED THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE, UNDER SUSPICION OF OPERATING VEHICLE UNDER INFLUENCE OF ALCOHOL AND OTHER OFFENSES. THERE WAS NO STRUCTURAL DAMAGE TO OUR VEHICLE, OTHER THAN THE PIPING SYSTEM. OUR DRIVER RECEIVED NO VIOLATIONS OR CITATIONS AND WAS ALLOWED TO LEAVE THE SCENE AFTER APPROXIMATELY ONE AND ONE HALF HOURS TIME.  MISSOULA FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE CRASH SCENE.  THE MAJORITY OF THE FUEL SPILL EVAPORATED.  THE REMAINING FUEL WAS CLEANING BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT BY ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THE WRECKER REMOVED THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS
column169: THIS INCIDENT WAS BEYOND OUR CONTROL. THE DESIGN FEATURES OF THE VEHICLE OPERATED COMPLETELY AS DESIGNED, WITHOUT FLAW. THE INTERNAL SHUT OFF VALVES OPERATED PROPERLY, SEALING THE CONTENTS INSIDE THE COMPARTMENT, ELIMINATING ANY FURTHER SPILLAGE. THE ONLY FUEL SPILL WAS FROM THE EXPOSED FILL LINES ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TANK COMPARTMENT.    ATTACHED PHOTOS - AT SCENE PHOTOS TAKEN BY SORENSEN AT SCENE OF INCIDENT.  DAY PHOTOS TAKEN BY SORENSEN AT OUR YARD FACILITY TO BETTER SHOW DAMAGE TO OUR VEHICLE.    ATTACHMENTS:    1. MISSOULA POLICE CRASH REPORT  2. MISSOULA FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORT  3. PHOTOS BY SORENSEN AT CRASH SCENE  4. PHOTOS BY SORENSEN OF TRUCK/TRAILER IN DAYLIGHT - TO CLARIFY DAMAGE TO EQUIPMENT  5. GOOGLE EARTH PRINT BY SORENSEN OF CRASH SCENE

column168: Sequence of events:  Cargo was loaded on the aircraft at MIA, there was no evidence of damage or any leaking on the containers when the cargo was inspected by the Florida West Load Supervisor.    During flight after takeoff from MIA the Load Supervisor went to do a routine check of the cargo and notice that one of the tanks was releasing gas thru the valves and notify the captain.    The tanks were secure however a big cloud was notice as a result of the tanks releasing gas in the main cargo compartment and the Load Supervisor left the compartment and closed the smoke barrier ( door).     The crew called Florida West Operation and notifies them of the incident.     The captain made the decision to return to MIA and declare an emergency.    Package failure details:  We were unable to get any details on the exact way the valves work from the shipper. It seem as if the valves just started to release a lot of gas.    Duration of leak:  Duration of the leak is unknown as the door to the cargo compartment was kept closed after the spill was noticed.    Mitigating the effects:  Upon noticing the leak the main cargo compartment was isolated from the crew by keeping the smoke barrier door closed. The ICAO ERG was consulted and follow the Drill Code that was indicated on the NOTOC for the items on position 4R where the gas was notice. The captain called flight control for additional advice. The flight follower called the emergency 24 hour number provided on the shippers declaration but didn’t get any answer. Without receiving advice from the shipper the Captain made the decision to return to Miami.
column169: The director of safety contacted the shipper to get more information on the shipment and was informed that the containers normally release some pressure. However we were not able to get any specifics on how to determine what is normal release of pressure and what is a leak of the material for a defective valve or too much pressure on the containers.    Per standard procedures, once a spill or leak is detected in the cargo compartment it is isolated and no one is permitted to re-enter to trouble shoot the problem. Our recommendation is that the shippers should better inform the carriers on the way this type of containers and valves work in order to better determine what is normal pressure release (venting) and what is hazmat spill.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While loading, two (2) four-gallon plastic pails were punctured by the forklift.  Approximately 8 gallons of free product were released.  The free product impacted the trailer floor and leaked outside of the trailer to the asphalt surface.  The trailer was isolated and Carolina Environmental Response Team (CERT) was dispatched to perform the cleanup.    CERT arrived and inspected the trailer.  CERT confirmed that two (2) four-gallon drums were damaged.  CERT deployed absorbent material to contain the free liquid.  The trailer was off-loaded and all free product and impacted debris were removed.  The damaged containers were placed into a 55-gallon drum for disposal.  The spent absorbent and debris were placed into two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal.    No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: An IBC container was being off-loaded from the truck using the lift gate and pallet jack. When the employee lowered the pallet jack the IBC container started to slide off the liftgate.  A forklift operator who was going to pick up the IBC container placed the forks on the metal plate of the metal cage to stop the container from sliding. Due to the weight of the IBC, the forks from the forklift went thru the plate and punctured the container. Immediately dikes were created around spill preventing it from spreading.  Clean Harbors response team completed the cleanup using additional sorbent material. The remaining product from IBC was transferred to another container, and all debris and spilled material that was cleaned up was placed into drums.  The IBC was disassembled and placed into a CYB and the drums with debris were released for transportation to the intended disposal facility.
column169: In order to prevent another incident like this, the facility will off-load all bulk containers using a dock on the other side of the facility.  The bulk containers will be moved to the back of the truck, where a forklift can safely pick up and move the containers to the permitted area of the warehouse.

column168: Driver failed to negotiate left hand turn at end of highway, truck and trailer rolled onto right side and came to rest right on top of a storm drain.  Cargo tank ruptured at seam with a foot long gash and spilled 175 barrels into the storm drain.  Rain shower occurred  after accident, washing oil into drain system leading to nearby bay.  Environmental response company was on site within the hour, and they deployed to the bay with spill containment booms to contain the spill.  Clean up was coordinated with Coast Guard and Texas state authorities.  Spill was declared completely cleaned up after 10 days of remediation.

column168: ON 06-20-15 @ 12:56, PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC. DISPATCH OFFICE RECEIVED A CALL FROM A COMPANY DRIVER, OUR DRIVER WAS REPORTING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AT 11128 HEMLOCK AVE. FONTANA CA 92337.  AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT ALL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE PRIMARY AND SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE ABOVE GROUND TANK THAT HE WAS DELIVERING INTO AND THERE WAS NO THREAT TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR THE GENERAL PUBLIC.  AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO SEND OVER PICTURES OF THE SPILL AND THE AREA OF THE SPILL. AT 12:59 PTL DISPATCH CONTACT THE COMPANIES SAFETY MANAGER TO REPORT THE SPILL AND THAT THE DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF SENDING PICTURES.  AT 13:10 OUR SAFETY MANAGER WAS IN CONTACT WITH THE COMPANIES CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY, PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL, PATRIOT WAS MADE AWARE OF THE TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED AND THE AMOUNT RELEASED.  PTL SAFETY MANAGER ARRIVED ON SITE @ 14:15 AND INSPECTED THE AREA AND VERIFIED THAT THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE AREA WAS SECURE. PTL'S CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY PROJECT MANAGER ARRIVED ON SCENE @ 14:30 AND INSPECTED THE AREA WITH PTL'S SAFETY MANAGER TO FORM AN ACTION PLAN FOR THE CLEAN UP. @ 14:5O PATRIOT'S CLEAN UP CREW ARRIVED ON SITE, A SAFETY MEETING WAS PERFORMED AND DIRECTION WAS GIVEN FOR THE CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE CLEANUP BEGAN @ 15:10 AND THE RESPONSE WAS TERMINATED @ 8:55.
column169: IT WAS FOUND IN OUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION THAT OUR DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY MONITOR THE ABOVE GROUND TANK GAUGE. IT WAS ALSO FOUND THAT THERE HAD BEEN RESTRICTED FLOW TO THE SECONDARY TANKS, DUE TO VALVE PLACEMENT, WHICH CAUSED THE PRODUCT NOT TO MANIFOLD PROPERLY CAUSING THE OVERFILL OF THE PRIMARY TANK.    PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC WILL BE RE INSTRUCTING ALL EMPLOYEES THAT DELIVER TO THIS SITE OR ANY OTHER THE IMPORTANCE OF MONITORING ALL TANK GAUGE SYSTEMS AND THE PROPER POSITION OF ALL VALVES FOR THE ABOVE GROUND TANK.

column168: DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED BY A MOTORIST THAT THEY COULD SMELL SOMETHING. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, CHEMTREC, AND THE NRC. WE ALSO SPOKE WITH STATE OF MISSOURI. UPON INPSECTION THEY FLANGE BOLTS THAT THEY COULD TIGHTEN FURTHER AND AFTER TIGHTENING THEM AND SOAPING THE FLANGE THERE WERE NO LEAKS.
column169: THE TRAILER WAS PRE-INSPECTED BEFORE THE LOAD AND NO LEAKS WERE FOUND.  WE ARE LOOKING AT WAYS THAT WE CAN FURTHER INSPECT THE TRAILERS BEFORE LOADED.

column168: WHILE ENROUTE FOR DELIVERY, HAZMAT DRIVER HAD TO COME TO AN ABRUPT SLOWDOWN DUE TO TRAFFIC SLOWING AND CHANGING LANES FOR A TROOPER WHO HAD A VEHICLE PULLED OVER AT THE SIDE OF ROAD. AS SOON AS PRACTICAL, THE DRIVER GOT OUT TO INSPECT THE LOAD, AT WHICH TIME, DISCOVERED THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED ALLOWING 6 TOTES TO MOVE FORWARD APPROX. 24-26 FT. INTO THE 6 TOTES LOADED IN THE NOSE OF TRAILER RESULTING IN A BRACKET ON ONE OF THE TOTES SLICING INTO ANOTHER CAUSING MATERIAL TO LEAK FROM GOUGED AREA ONTO TRAILER FLOOR. ALTHOUGH THE TOTES WERE STRAPPED, THEY DID NOT HOLD DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF THE TOTES. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE SLICE IN THE PLASTIC TOTE, THERE WAS NO MEANS AVAILABLE TO MITIGATE THE LEAK. THE DRIVER PLACED SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBENT SOCKS AT THE BACK OF TRAILER AS A PRECAUTION AND BECAUSE THE TRAILER HAD A STEEL SEALED FLOOR AND 8 INCH HIGH STEEL CONTAINMENT END GATE, THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO DRIVE TO OUR CLOSEST TERMINAL. UPON EXAMINING THE LOAD ON ARRIVAL AT OUR CINCINNATI TERMINAL, APPROX. 200 GALS. HAD ESCAPED FROM TOTE ONTO TRAILER FLOOR.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER.
column169: THE TOTES WERE NOT PROPERLY LOADED AT THE 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY: 6 TOTES IN THE NOSE WITH 3 STRAPS, APPROX. 26FT GAP, 6 MORE TOTES, 3 STRAPS ON BACK AND 3 ON FRONT. HAZMAT WILL WORK WITH THE TRANSFER FACILITY TO DEVELOP A PROCEDURE TO SECURE TOTES IN A SAFER MANNER, SUGGESTING: SINGLE TOTES DOWN THE MIDDLE-AT MINIMUM, 1 STRAP OVER TOP OF EACH TOTE APPLYING DOWNWARD PRESSURE, 2 STRAPS ON BACK. IF ENOUGH STRAPS ARE AVAILABLE, 2 STRAPS OVER EACH ONE.    HAZMAT WILL SEND A FLEET MESSAGE VIA QUALCOMM INSTRUCTING DRIVERS TO CONTACT HAZMAT'S OPERARIONS DEPT. FOR SECUREMENT GUIDANCE WHEN PICKING UP TOTES.

column168: THE DELIVERY DRIVER MISTAKENLY PUMP AN ESTIMATED 20 GALS OF A 12.5% SODIUM SOLUTION(BLEACH) INTO A VESSEL CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 40 GALS OF A CORROSION/SCALE INHIBITOR NALCO 3D TRASAR 3D T265.  THE MIXTURE RESULTED IN A CHEMICAL REACTION.  TANK LACKED COMPANY STANDARD COMPANY STANDARD MARKINGS.    AS INTERNAL REPORTING WAS MADE, AND A COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE WAS SENT TO THE SCENE. AFTER ARRIVING ON SCENE AND DETERMINING THAT THE REACTION HAD CEASED AND UPON SMELLING A FAINT ODOR OF CHLORINE A CALL WAS PLACED AT 15:25 IN WHICH THE POTENTIAL TO HAVE EXCEEDED RQ FOR CHLORINE WAS DISCOVERED. AT 15:35 A CALL WAS PLACED TO THE NRC REPORTING THE POTENTIAL OF THE OFF GAS.    THE BLEACH/CORROSION INHIBITOR WAS PUMPED OUT AND REMOVED FORM THE SITE TO HAWKINS APOPKA PROPERTY. DURING THIS PROCESS WATER WAS ADDED BRINGING THE TOTAL VOLUME OF THE MIXTURE TO 90GALS AND A PH OF 8.    FURTHER TESTING FOR AVAILABLE CHLORINE IN THE MIXTURE SHOWED THAT THE OFF GAS COULD NOT HAVE EXCEEDED THE RQ FOR CHLORINE (10LBS), BUT ACTUAL VOLUME OF RELEASE IS NOT ABLE TO BE CALCULATED.

column168: Driver was uncoupling hose from trailer after unloading product. The driver utilized the customer 5 gallon bucket and placed the bucket underneath the trailer and hose connection at the back of the trailer. As the driver began to unhook the hose from the customer end of the line, the bucket began to leak and caused the product to spill on the ground. Approximately two ounces were released before the driver tipped the bucket to stop the leak. The spill was immediately controlled and the area cleaned. The bucket had a small crack in the bottom that was not visible because of dried product residue on the bottom of the bucket. Trimac will supply the drivers clean new buckets to use and not rely in the customer to supply this type of containment.
column169: The five gallon bucket is the normal containment device in case there is any product spill from uncoupling hoses.Trimac is reviewing the process trying to develop a more efficient type of containment in case there is any product heel in the hose. Until them we will begin supplying new clean buckets to the drivers and not rely customer supplied buckets where Trimac has not control.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TURNING LEFT ONTO SOUTHBOUND RESERVE ST. FROM STOCKYARD ROAD WESTBOUND. AFTER COMPLETING HIS TURN, OTHER VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED ON RESERVE ST, COLLIDED WITH CENTER DIVIDER IN ROADWAY, COLLIDING INTO DECORATIVE TREES AND SHRUBBERY. AT THIS POINT VEHICLE CONTINUED PAST CENTER DIVIDER AND INTO LEFT TURN LANE ON RESERVE STREET NORTH BOUND. VEHICLE THEN ENCROACHED INTO SOUTHBOUND LANE AND COLLIDED WITH OUR COMPANY TRAILER, WHICH WAS COMPLETING TURN SOUTHBOUND ONTO RESERVE ST. FROM STOCKYARD ROAD EASTBOUND. VEHICLE COLLIDED WITH LEFT REAR OF OUR TRAILER, MAKING CONTACT WITH LEFT SIDE PIPING OF UNDER CARRIAGE OF THE TRAILER. COLLISION OCCURRED IN SOUTHBOUND LANE, OTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTHBOUND. THE PIPING SYSTEM WAS FULL OF GASOLINE, APPROXIMATELY 12 GALLONS IN THE PIPING SYSTEM, DUE TO JUST HAVING BEEN LOADED. DRIVER HAD JUST LEFT LOADING FACILITY. MISSOULA POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS ARRIVED ON SCENE. DUE TO THE FUEL SPILL AND POTENTIAL OF FIRE RISK, THE ROADWAY WAS CLOSED TEMPORARILY, FOR LESS THAN ONE HOUR. MISSOULA POLICE ARRESTED THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE, UNDER SUSPICION OF OPERATING VEHICLE UNDER INFLUENCE OF ALCOHOL AND OTHER OFFENSES. THERE WAS NO STRUCTURAL DAMAGE TO OUR VEHICLE, OTHER THAN THE PIPING SYSTEM. OUR DRIVER RECEIVED NO VIOLATIONS OR CITATIONS AND WAS ALLOWED TO LEAVE THE SCENE AFTER APPROXIMATELY ONE AND ONE HALF HOURS TIME.  MISSOULA FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE CRASH SCENE. THE MAJORITY OF THE FUEL SPILL EVAPORTATED. THE REMAINING FUEL WAS CLEANED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT BY ABSORBENT MATERIALS. THE WRECKER REMOVED THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS.
column169: THIS INCIDENT WAS BEYOND OUR CONTROL. THE DESIGN FEATURES OF THE VEHICLE OPERATED COMPLETELY AS DESIGNED, WITHOUT FLAW. THE INTERNAL SHUT OFF VALVES OPERATED PROPERLY, SEALING THE CONTENTS INSIDE THE COMPARTMENT, ELIMINATING ANY FURTHER SPILLAGE. THE ONLY FUEL SPILL WAS FROM THE EXPOSED FILL LINES ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TANK COMPARTMENT.    ATTACHED PHOTOS - AT SCENE TAKEN BY SORENSEN AT SCENE OF INCIDENT.  DAY PHOTOS TAKEN BY SORENSEN AT OUR YARD FACILITY TO BETTER SHOW DAMAGE TO OUR VEHICLE.    ATTACHMENTS:  1. MISSOULA POLICE CRASH REPORT  2. MISSOULA FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORT  3. PHOTOS BY SORENSEN AT CRASH SCENE  4. PHOTOS BY SORENSEN OF TRUCK/TRAILER IN DAYLIGHT - TO CLARIFY DAMAGE TO EQUIPMENT  5. GOOGLE EARTH PRINT BY SORENSEN OF CRASH SCENE

column168: Accident is still under investigation and the driver has not proven truthful about what happened.  Driver called me (the owner) at 5:15 a.m. before he called emergency services.  I asked if he was okay and told him to hang up and call 911 so emergency response could find him and to make sure he told them he was loaded with flammable hazardous materials.  He was not sure where he was.  I got in my car and headed in the direction where I knew he should be coming.  I received a call from Minnesota pollution control about an hour later and they informed me where the truck was and that driver had been taken to hospital.  I am still waiting on the accident report from Minnesota State Patrol.  After talking to driver later - Driver said he was on I-90 and claimed he coughed and passed out.  Drove the truck down a 250' embankment and hit a tree where truck then laid over in mud on right side.  Driver does not remember hitting tree but says he woke up on the way down.  The semi was almost upside down.  It was laying over a spring-fed creek that is the water supply for the Town of St. Charles Minnesota.  The tanker did not leak until the sun came up.  Then it only leaked out of the front compartment manhole cover.  Approximately 150 gallons was contained by the St. Charles Fire Department in containers.  Waste Central and Clean Harbors took away the spilled material.  I sent another one of my trucks to St. Charles and later in the day, holes were drilled in the wrecked tanker and we pumped the rest of the product off.  When the wrecked truck was uprighted, the diesel tank came off the passenger side and spilled some diesel.  Minnesota Pollution control tested the site for two days and no further clean-up was required for either the ethanol or the diesel fuel.
column169: I actually can't think of anything at this time.  I feel that Minnesota Pollution Control and the St. Charles Fire Department as well as DOT and State Patrol did an excellent job in containing the situation and the professionalism was outstanding.

column168: On 06/22/2015 CPUC Hazmat Inspector Michael Max was conducting and inspection of rail cars in the San Joaquin Valley Railroad Bakersfield Yard. During that inspection Mr. Max found that three load tank cars containing Petroleum Crude Oil were venting from the tops of the cars. The cars were GROX 132057, GROX 132061, and GROX 132077. Mr. Max listed the cause of the leak to be the "fittings flange plate located on the top of the tank car." Patriot Environmental was contacted to re-mediate the leaking cars but found that there was a construction defect to the cars and that they would have to be unloaded and sent home shop to address the defects. Currently the three cars are being held in the SJVR Bakersfield Yard awaiting OTMA from the FRA to be moved to the customer to offload.

column168: ON MONDAY, JUNE 8, 2015, OUR DRIVER LEFT THE SUNOCO TERMINAL IN WASKOM, TEXAS, ON ROUTE TO ATLANTA, TEXAS.  HE WAS LOADED WITH 8800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  AS HE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON TEXAS HIGHWAY 43, A LIGHT COLORED PASSENGER CAR PULLED OUT OF FM 805 IN FRONT OF HIM.  IN AN EFFORT TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH THE AUTOMOBILE, THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE TANKER TRUCK HE WAS OPERATING AND IMPACTED THE BRIDGE RAILING ON THE EAST SIDE OF HIGHWAY 43. THE TRACTOR MADE CONTACT WITH THE RAIL AT ENOUGH OF AN ANGLE TO CAUSE THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO RIDE THE RAILING FOR A NUMBER OF FEET BEFORE BREAKING THROUGH AND GOING OVER THE CREEKS' CONCRETE ABUTMENT AND COMING TO REST ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. SHORTLY AFTER THE TRACTOR CAME TO A STOP, THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO EXIT THE TRACTOR, WHICH THEN CAUGHT FIRE, COMPLETELY DESTROYING THE TRACTOR, TRAILER AND BURNING THE FUEL THAT WAS LOADED IN THE TRAILER.    IT IS ASSUMED THE TRAILOR WAS RIPPED OPEN WHEN IT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE BRIDGE RAILING.  THE TEXAS DOT, TEXAS FORESTRY SERVICE AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS, AS WELL AS THE TCEQ WERE ON THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY. SOUTHLAND RESPONSE, A HAZ-MAT TEAM OUT OF LONGVIEW, TEXAS, WAS CALLED IN AND BEGAN CORRECTIVE ACTION IMMEDIATELY.  THE MAJORITY OF THE GASOLINE ON THE TRAILER BURNED, AND WHAT LITTLE THAT WAS LEFT WAS REMOVED BY THE HAZ-MAT TEAM. A WRECKER WAS CALLED TO REMOVED WHAT WAS LEFT OF THE TRUCK AND TRAILER.
column169: 1. ADDITIONAL DRIVER TRAINING ON ACCIDENT AVOIDANCE.  2. WORKING CLOSER WITH OUR INSURANCE COMPANY ON SAFETY TRAINING.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: IN THE DARK AND RAIN OUR DRIVER HAD LOADED TO MUCH NL GASOLINE ONTO THE TRANSPORT TANKER, ONCE THE IN-GROUND TANK REACHED 90% VOLUME CAPACITY, THE STORE ALARMS WENT OFF AND THE DRIVER FELT A JERK ON THE HOSE,. HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE FLOW AND AS THE DRIVER UNHOOKED THE FITTINGS, LESS THE 2 QUARTS WAS RELEASED ONTO CONCRETE, HE CLEANED IT UP WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD. AFTER THAT TIME ALL HOSES AND FITTINGS WERE UNHOOKED AND LOADED ONTO THE TANKER. THE DRIVER ENTERED THE STORE TO TELL THEM HE WOULD HAVE TO TAKE THE RETAINED GALLONS TO THE STORE NEAR BY AND WOULD RETURN WITH THE DELIVERY PAPERS. AFTER HE LEFT, A CUSTOMER CALLED THE FIRE DEPT. CLAIMING FUEL CAME FORM THE BUCKET AND WAS GOING DOWN THE HILL, MOST OF THIS STORY WAS BASED ON THE SMELL OF GAS WHEN THE WITNESS WAS PUMPING GAS. THE STORE MANAGER CALLED OUR DISPATCHER WHO CALLED THE DRIVER AND HIS REGIONAL SUPERVISOR. THEY RETURNED TO THE SITE TO FIND ONLY A SHEEN ON RAIN PUDDLES AND NO FUEL IN ANY OF THE DROP BUCKETS OR STORM DRAINS. DUE TO THE WET CONCRETE, OVERFILLED TANK, SPLIT OR RETAINED LOAD AND UNRELIABLE WITNESS, THE EXACT GALLONS WERE ALL BASED ON BEST GUESS ESTIMATES. TAS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED BY STAR TO EVALUATE THE POSSIBLE SPILL. MICROBES WERE SPREAD OUT AND PADS USED. NO FUEL WAS FOUND IN STORM DRAINS, DROP BUCKETS OR CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE SOIL. THIS SHOWS US THAT EVEN THE SMALLEST GUESSES ON GALLONS LOST ARE STILL OVER STATED GREATLY.
column169: THE PRIMARY RECOMMENDATION TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF RELEASE, IS TO CHECK THE STICK READINGS AND COMPARE TO THE ATG BEFORE DROPPING TO VERIFY THE AMOUNT THAT CAN SAFELY FIT BEFORE THE DROP TAKES PLACE.  ANOTHER SUGGESTION WOULD BE TO ALLOW A SLOW VENT INSIDE THE TANK ITSELF SO THE PRESSURE FROM HITTING THE 90% FULL MARK WOULD STOP THE FILLING BUT WOULD NOT MAKE A MESS TO UNHOOK FROM.

column168: An odor was reported emitting from cars on head end of train QSRHOB-18.  Inspection of tank car TILX 200159 found product leaking from a failed a Pyco Thermo Probe located under the combination housing. Car was vented to relieve internal tank pressure to stop the release of product.  A temporary cover was secured over the housing of the thermo probe assembly.  The car was then moved to an isolation track where a 3 inch threaded stainless steel nipple and cap were threaded into the body of thermo probe housing to secure the car from further leakage.  The car was then released and the shipper moved the car back to point of origin under an OTMA-3 for further repairs and handling.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: Quick Fuel Fleet Services employee was fueling equipment at Medegen Medical Products utilizing a mobile fueling truck. Quick Fuel employee placed fueling hose and nozzle on back of stake truck while moving truck to fuel additional customer equipment. While moving truck at the customer property, the hose and nozzle fell to the ground and the dispensing nozzle seperated from the hose causing a 10 gallon dyed diesel fuel release on concrete and asphalt surface. A Medegen employeee called the Fire Department and the National Response Center to report the release. Quick Fuel employees cleaned up the spill using oil dry and placing the waste material in a container for proper disposal. Fire Department personnel observed the cleanup process. The diesel fuel never reached a water body, sewer or any permeable material and was completely removed from the impermeable asphalt/concrete surface to the satisfaction of our customer.
column169: The Quick Fuel Fleet Services employee was retrained to completely wind up the dispensing hose on the reel and place the nozzle in the cradle prior to moving the fuel truck.

column168: THIS IS A 49 CFR 171.15(B)(2) REPORT. PACKAGE WAS CRUSHED DURING SORT OPERATIONS AT THE MEMPHIS HUB ON FRIDAY NIGHT JUNE 26 2015 AND THE TWO INNER SCRE TOP VIALS CONTAINING THREE RADIOACTIVE CAPSULES CAME OUT OF THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS REWRAPPED AND CONTINUED TO BOSTON ARRIVING AT THE FEDEX EXPRESS BOSTON LOGAN RAMP ON SATURDAY MORNING, JUNE 27 2015. WHERE IT WAS TRUCKED TO THE FRAMINGHAM STATION AND THEN TRANSFERRED BY TRUCK TO THE WEST BOLYSTON STATION, WHERE IT REMAINED UNTIL MONDAY JUNE 29 2015 IT WAS DELIVERED TO WORCESTOR PLYTECHNIC INSTITUTE, WHO DETERMINED THE PACKAGE WAS MISSING THE RADIOACTIVE CONTENTS. FEDEX EXPRESS WAS NOTIFIED BY THE SHIPPER, SOURCE PRODUCTION AND EQUIPMENT COMPANY (SPEC) AT 1:20 PM MONDAY, JUNE 29 2015 THAT THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN DELIVERED BUT THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL CONTENTS WERE MISSING.    THE TWO INNER CONTAINERS WERE GLASS SCREW TOP VIALS 1.875 IN HEIGHT AND 0.63 CENTIMETER IN DIAMETER. ONE VIAL CONTAINED ONE SE-75 TITANIUM CAPSULE, 5.7 MBQ, 1 MM DIAMETER BY 5 MM LENGTH. THE SECOND VIAL CONTAINED 47.0 MBQ YB-169 TITANIUM CAPSULES, 0.8 MM DIAMETER BY 4.5 MM LENGTH  FEDEX EXPRESS INITIATED RADIATION SURVEYS AT THE MEMPHIS HUB, NEW ORLEANS RAMP, BOSTON LOGAN RAMP, FRAMINGHAM STATION, WEST BOYLSTON STATION. RADIATION SURVEYS WERE CONDUCTED ON THE ULD’S AND ALL VEHICLES USED IN THE BOSTON AREA WHICH CONTAINED THE PACKAGE. INTERVIEWS WERE CONDUCTED WITH ALL PERSONNEL IDENTIFIED AS HANDLING THE PACKAGE. ADDITIONAL RADIATION SURVEYS WERE CONDUCTED BY THE MASSACHUSETTS RADIATION CONTROL AGENCY OF THE FEDEX EXPRESS STATIONS, VEHICLE AND EQUIPMENT ASSOCIATED WITH THE MOVEMENT OF THE PACKAGE. THE TENNESSEE RADIATION CONTROL AGENCY CONDUCTED RADIATION SURVEYS AT THE MEMPHIS HUB AND THE LOUISIANA RADIATION CONTROL AGENCY ALSO CONDUCTED RADIATION SURVEY AT THE NEW ORLEANS RAMP: ALL RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE.    ON FRIDAY, JULY 10 2015 A MEMPHIS LANDFILL OPERATOR REPORTED TO FEDEX EXPRESS THAT A DUMPSTER COMPACTOR AHD BEEN RECEIVED FROM THE MEMPHIS HUB WHICH ACTIVATED THE RADIATION ALARM. THE DUMPSTER WAS RETURNED TO THE MEMPHIS HUB WHERE THE CONTENTS WERE UNLOADED IN A CONTROLLED MANNER AND THE RADIOACTIVITY WAS ISOLATED BY FEDEX EXPRESS PERSONNEL. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT IN THE IDENTIFIED DEBRIS A TEAL COLORED SCREW TOP VIAL WAS BROKEN. THIS MEANT THAT ONE OR MORE OF THE VERY SMALL TITANIUM CAPSULES WERE LOOSE IN THE DEBRIS. FEDEX EXPRESS WAS NOT EQUIPPED TO RECOVER THE SMALL RADIOACTIVE TITANIUM CAPSULES, SO THE SHIPPER SPEC WAS CALLED IN TO COMPLETE THE RECOVERY.    SPEC ARRIVED AT THE MEMPHIS HUB ON SATURDAY MORNING JULY 11 2015 AND RECOVERED ON RADIOACTIVE CAPSULE.NO OTHER ACTIVITY WAS DETECTED. THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATION. SPEC TRANSPORTED THE SOURCE BACK TO THEIR FACILITY IN ST. ROSE LOUISIANA. THE LOUISIANA RADIATION CONTROL AGENCY WAS REQUESTED BY FEDEX EXPRESS TO OBTAIN A GAMMA SPECTRUM OF THE RECOVERED SOURCE, WHICH WAS ANALYZED BY THE DOMESTIC NUCLEAR DETECTION OFFICE, WHO IDENTIFIED SE-75.  CONCLUSION: THE TWO YB-169

column168: DRIVER LEFT HIS DELIVERY AT THE 10686 FM 2932 HEADING NORTH AT ROUGHLY 2:30  P.M. 6/22/2015. DRIVER WENT LESS THAN 1 MILE WHEN HE FELT THE TRUCK PULL TO THE RIGHT AND WENT OFF THE EDGE OF THE ROAD. ABOUT 30 FEET FORWARD HE HIT A DRIVEWAY THAT SLOSHED THE TRUCK SIDE TO SIDE AND HE NO LONGER HAD CONTROL OF THE TRUCK. HE CAME BACK ONTO THE ROAD WITH THE TRUCK LEANING.  THE TRUCK ROLLED ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE AND SLID ACROSS THE ROAD, HITTING ANOTHER DRIVEWAY FORCING THE TRUCK TO FLIP END OVER END ONTO THE DRIVERS SIDE .THE DRIVER EXITED THE VEHICLE AND USED THE PHONE OF A BYSTANDER TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARMTNET AND HIS OFFICE MANAGER. THE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN MINUTES. ONCE HIS MANAGER ARRIVED HE WAS TAKEN TO THE AMBULANCE TO TEXAS HEALTH PRESBYTERIAN HOSPITAL OF ROCKWALL, TX.    THE DELIVERY HOSE CAUGHT ON FIRE AND BURNED. THE PRESSURE GAUGE FACE PLATE BROKE AND WAS LEAKING. WHEN THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED THEY EXTINGUISHED THE HOSE FIRE.  THE PRESSURE GUAGE WAS LEAKING JUST ENOUGH THAT WHEN OUR SERVICE DEPARMENT ARRIVED THEY TOOK THE GAUGE OUT AND PLUGGED THE FITTING.  MINIMAL LOSS OF PRODUCT. AS FAR AS PACKAGE FAILURE I BELIEVE THERE WAS NONE.
column169: I DID SUGGEST ADDITIONAL DRIVER TRAINING. ON BEING THE SMITH SYSTEM INC. I DO IN HOUSE DRIVER TRAINING. EARLIER THIS YEAR I HELD A CLASS ON OVER STEERING.  I TALKED TO THIS PARTICULAR DRIVER ABOUT WHAT HE WOULD DO IN THE EVENT OF GOING OFF THE ROAD AND HE SAID HE WOULD RIDE IT OUT UNTIL HE COULD STOP OR SAFELY PULL BACK ONTO THE ROAD. HOWEVER THERE WAS A DRIVEWAY IN HIS WAY.
