PARTIALLY OFF THE NARROW HIGHWAY SHOULDER AND PARTIALLY ON THE ONCOMING TRAFFIC LANE.   THE VENT (BETWEEN THE OVERTURNE RAILS) DUE TO THE DISTORTED OF THE TANK WAS BROKEN AND OR DISCONNECTED BEGAN LEAKING PRODUCT FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR BEFORE FIRST RESPONDERS ARRIVED AND BEGAN TO RECAPTURE LEAKING PRODUCT IN BUCKETS AND DRUMS AND DAMNED THE DITCH PREVENTING PRODUCT RUN OFF.
column169: OUR CONTRACTOR/DRIVER IS WELL TRAINED AND WAS OPERATING PROPERLY; HIS EQUIPMENT WAS IN PROPER CONDITION. I THINK IT WORTH MENTIONING THAT HE ALMOST CERTAINLY PREVENTED FATALITY OF THE SUV DRIVE BY HIS EVASIVE MANEUVER. IT IS POSSIBLE THAT SAID MANEUVER SAVED HIS OWN LIFE ALSO. RATHER THAN HIS TRANSPORT BEING A TOTAL LOSS AND LOSING EIGHT WEEKS AT WORK.   INCIDENTALLY AS BEFORE INDICATED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DID NOT CAUSE HIS INJURY; THE RESULT WOULD HAVE BEEN THE SAME NO MATTER WHAT THE CARGO WAS. WE HAVE EXPERIENCED EXORBITANT CHARGES BECAUSE THE LOAD WAS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

ON JUNE 22 2015, GAINCO CREW MOBED TO A JOB LOCATED AT 2206 INDUSTRIAL ROAD IN ALICE TEXAS. THE CREW PROCEEDED TO SETUP THE EQUIPMENT ALONG WITH A TEMPORARY DECON AREA. ONCE THE EQUIPMENT AND DECON AREA WERE SET UP. GAINCO’S OPERATOR, CHRIS ROBINSON, BEGAN TO OFF LOAD TOTES OF SODIUM PERMANGANATE (REMOXL). AT APPROXIMATELY 14:30 CST, WHILE CHRIS ROBINSON WAS OFFLOADING THE TOTES, HE ACCIDENTLY PUNCTURED THE TOTES CAUSING THE SODIUM PERMANGANATE TO RELEASE ONTO THE SOIL. THE PUNCTURE WHOLE IS LOCATED AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE AND IS APPROXIMATELY THREE INCHES IN SIZE. GAINCO CREW IMMEDIATELY STOPPED ALL ACTIVITY TO RESPOND TO THE RELEASE. APPROXIMATELY 210 GALLONS OF SODIUM PERMANGANATE WAS SPILLED EAST OF FACILITY, WITHIN A FENCED IN AREA OF THE FIELD APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET OF THE INTERSECTION OF INDUSTRIAL BLVD AND ALAMO DR (APPROXIMATELY 50 FEET NORTH OF THE FENCE). NO SURFACE WATERS WERE IMPACTED OR THREATENED. NO POTENTIAL WATER POLLUTION OR HARMFUL IMPACTS TO THE ENVIRONMENT AND/OR IDENTIFICATION OF ANY ENVIRONMENT SENSITIVE AREAS OR NATURAL RESOURCES ARE RISK. THE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH APPROXIMATELY 40 LB OF FERROUS SULFATE. THE IMPACTED AREA WAS EXCAVATED, USING THE PURPLE COLOR AS A VISUAL INDICATOR. IMPACTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND PLACED INTO A ROLL OFF CONTAINER FOR PROPER OFFICE DISPOSAL. A CONCRETE SLAB ENCOUNTERED DURING THE REMOVAL OF THE IMPACTED SOIL, WAS SPRAYED WITH A 1:1 MIXTURE OF VINEGAR AND HYDROGEN PEROXIDE TO NEUTRALIZE ANY REMAINING CHEMICAL ON THE SLAB. ON JUNE 23 2015 THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #1120678) AND THE TEXAS SPILL REPORTING HOTLINE (REPORT #20152329) WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL. A SAMPLE WAS COLLECTED FROM THE ROLL OF BOX, THE REMEDIATED AREA AND THE BACKGROUND AREA.  THE SAMPLES WERE SUBMITED TO ANALYSIS FOR DETERMINATION OF POTASSIM SODIUM AND PH CONCENTRAIONS. ONE LABORATORY ANALYSIS WERE RECEIVED, A PROFILE WAS PREPARED AND SUBMITTED TO US ECOLOGY. GAINCO, INC IS WAITING ON APPROVAL. ONCE APPROVED, GAINCO WILL TRANSPORT THE ROLLOF TO US ECOLOGY FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: GAINCO INC, WAS OFF LOADING THE MATERIAL IN WET, MUDDY CONDITION WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE INCIDENT. GAINCO INC WILL NOT ALLOW FORKLIFTS TO OPERATE AROUND TOTES IN THE FUTURE IN SIMILAR CIRCUMSTANCES. ADDITIONAL TRAINING OF THE CREW WAS PERFORMED.

column168: CUSTOMER HAS AN ABOVE GROUND TANK. TO DELIVER WE USE POWER TAKE OFF (PTO) PUMP ON TRACTOR TO MOVE PRODUCT THROUGH PIPES AND HOSES. PTO HAS DUAL OUTLETS TO UNLOAD ON DRIVERS SIDE OR CURB SIDE. DRIVER USED DRIVER SIDE AND FAILED TO SECURE PIPE END TO CURB SIDE END.  DURATION: 45-60 SECONDS. TURNED OFF PTO, PLACED ABSORBENT SOCKS AROUND DRAINS AND SPILL. DISBURSED FLOOR DRY ABSORBENT AND CALLED HELP IN TO CONTINUE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP. HELP DISPERSED MORE FLOOR DRY AND PLUMBERS ENVIRONMENT COMPANY CAME IN TO VACUUM OUT OIL/WATER SEPARATOR PIT.
column169: ADDITIONAL SAFETY REVIEW AND TRAINING TOOK PLACE. LOCKING CLASPS WERE PURCHASED AND ATTACHED TO ALL CAMS AND CAM ARMS ON ALL TRACTORS TO SECURE IN PLACE AT ALL TIMES ON BOTH SIDES OF PTO.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: The trailer contained a mixture of acetaldehyde, vinyl acetate, and methyl acetate.  The vinyl acetate reacted to form polyvinyl acetate.  This reaction generated heat (and pressure) that built up inside the trailer, causing the safety pressure valve on the trailer to relieve and vent to the atmosphere.   06/19/2015  08:00 – Truck driver dropped off trailer  13:00 – Site personnel loaded trailer.  06/22/2015  09:00 – Truck driver arrived and hooked up to trailer.  09:15 – Truck driver started moving trailer and heard a humming sound.  09:20 – Truck driver stopped to investigate and determined trailer was venting.  09:25 – Truck driver opened the manual vent on the trailer for additional venting.  09:25 – Site personnel confirmed incident and cleared area to a safe location.  09:35 – Water deluge was put on trailer to cool contents.  09:45 – Plant emergency system activated.  11:25 – Trailer temperature stabilized.  12:35 – Added 10 gallons of inhibitor to the trailer.  13:30 – Moved trailer back into loading area and reconnected to plant flare.  14:00 – Incident all-clear announced.
column169: The reaction was determined to have started inside the storage tank from a low concentration of inhibitor, and potentially caustic contamination.  The operating procedure requires 1 gallon of inhibitor to be added to the storage tank after each loading activity.  To prevent recurrence the following action items will be implemented:  • The type and amount of inhibitor required will be confirmed with the vendor.  • An automated inhibitor addition system will be evaluated.  • The inhibitor concentration in the tank will be periodically measured.  • A maximum temperature will be established for the tank.

column168: ON JUNE 17, 2015 AT ~12:00 PM DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF FERRIC CHLORIDE WHEN A LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE REAR SUMP AREA OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER  IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE UNLOADING PROCESS AND DISCOVERED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE SUMP PLATE UNDER THE TRAILER. DRIVER CONTACTED PVST'S DISPATCH FOR  ASSISTANCE. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE LEAK BY RELIEVING THE PRESSURE FROM THE TRAILER WHICH SLOWED THE LEAK BUT DID NOT STOP IT. HE ALSO TRIED  TIGHTENING THE BOLTS ON THE SUMP PLATE WITH NO SUCCESS. BUCKETS WERE PLACED UNDER THE TRAILER TO TRY AND CONTAIN SOME OF THE LEAKING MATERIAL WHILE THE  GROUP TRIED TO CONTAIN THE LEAK. THE PLANT OPERATORS AND THE DRIVER USED A 3" HOSE AND LIMESTONE TO DIKE THE AREA. A PLASTIC POOL WAS THEN PLACED UNDER  THE TRAILER REPLACING THE BUCKETS AT THE POINT OF THE LEAK AS A CONTAINMENT CONTAINER. A DRUM PUMP WAS THEN USED TO PUMP THE MATERIAL FROM THE POOL  INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS .MEANWHILE, A TEAM FROM PVST WAS DISPATCH TO THE C/O FLINT TO ASSIST IN THE SITUATION. UPON ARRIVING THE GROUP TRIED TO REPLACE SOME  OF THE SUMP BOLTS BUT HAD NO SUCCESS. SO IT WAS DETERMINED TO PUMP THE MATERIAL FROM TRAILER 63A, THE LEAKING TRAILER, INTO TRAILER 65A THAT WAS  DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. ONCE THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TRAILER 65A THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED INTO THE CUSTOMER'S TANK.
column169: CHECK SUMP PLATES ON TRAILERS 30A AND 62A THAT WERE BOTH RUBBER LINED AROUND THE SAME TIME. RINSE OUT TRAILER AND DROP AND INSPECT THAT PLATE ARE  INSTALLED CORRECTLY. ORDER EQUIPMENT TO PERFORM CONDUCTIVITY TEST ON RUBBER LINED EQUIPMENT AFTER LOADING. REQUEST AN INCIDENT INVESTIGATION FROM  VENDOR.

column168: ON TUESDAY JUNE 23, 2015 AROUND 18:00 DRIVER HOOKED UP TRAILER MB23 TO THE CUSTOMERS UNLOADING TO DELIVER A LOAD OF BLEACH. HE STARTED THE PTO TO AIR UP THE TRAILER. AT 10 PSI THE MATERIAL STARTED TO UNLOAD. WHILE INSPECTING THE UNLOADING SYSTEM BY CHECKING THE HOOKUP CONNECTION AND HOSE CONNECTIONS BLEACH WAS DETECTED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. BLEACH WAS LEAKING FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE AREA UNDER THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE EMERGENCY VALVE ON THE TRAILER AND SHUT OFF THE AIR. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER APPROXIMATELY 1-3 GALLONS LEAKED FROM AREA (DUE TO RAIN THERE WAS PUDDLES UNDER THE TRAILER). THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE CUSTOMER AND CONTACTED DISPATCH.
column169: IMPROVE POST-MAINTENANCE AND PRE-TRIP TRAILER INSPECTIONS.

A Veolia employee picked up and transported two 5 gallon plastic jerricans of acid/solvent waste from a generator location.  The employee was unaware that the mixture in the containers were undergoing a chemical reaction.  The  sealed plastic jerricans built up pressure and bulged.  The employee identified the bulging drums at another location.  He overpacked each of the Jerricans into their own 10 gallon overpack.  At a third customer location one of the inner 5 gallon jerricans ruptured.  The pressure blew the lid off of the overpack.  Contents of the acid/solvent waste splashed throughout the trailer.  Some liquid contents leaked out of the trailer and onto a small section of the customer's asphalt parking lot. The employee susstained an acid exposure to his eyes.  The employee flushed his eyes and body at an emergency eyewash/shower station.  The employee was taken to the emergency room for treatment and released that evening.  The local fire department hazmat team contained the spill.  Later that evening an environmental remediation company decontaminated the truck and asphalt.  The following day Veolia employees in chemical and ballistic suits repackaged the 2nd drum into a 55 gallon steel overpack with a pressure relief valve.
column169: The customer was notified of the incident.  The customer will no longer mix the two products that reacted.  Each of the chemical components will be packaged, stored, and treated independantly.  Awareness training was provided to Veolia employees.

column168: DRIVER JOHN FINK WAS TRAVELING WB ON I-26 NEAR MM 17 IN SOUTH CAROLINA AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30AM ON JUNE 26, 2015. HE HAD FINISHED LOADING HIS TRUCK WITH GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL ABOUT 15-20 MINUTES EARLIER AT THE KINDER MORGAN TERMINAL IN SPARTANBURG, SC.    JOHN IS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN FOLLOWING (NOT NECESSARILY IN THE SAME LANE) AN SUV (LABLED AS V2 IN THE ATTACHED DIAGRAM) AS HIS TRACTOR-TRAILER APPROACHED THE WB ON-RAMP OF THE INTERCHANGE AT MM 17. ANOTHER SUV (LABELED AS V1 IN TEH ATTACHED DIAGRAM) IS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN TRAVELING ON THE WB ON-RAMP AT THIS TIME, PREPARING TO ENTER THE INTERSTATE ROADWAY.    THE INITIAL THEORY PUT FORTH BY THE HP AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT SUGGESTED THAT V1 AND V2 INTERFERED WITH ONE ANOTHER AS V1 ATTEMPTED TO ENTER THE ROADWAY.  THE INTERFERENCE MAY HAVE BEEN A COLLISION BETWEEN V1 AND V2, OR SEVERE SWERVING OR BRAKING BY EITHER VEHICLE. THE THEORY CONTINUES THAT THE INTERACTION BETWEEN V1 AND V2 RESULTED IN EITHER A COLLISION THAT AFFECTED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER (V3) DIRECTLY OR CREATED AND INSTANTANEOUS OBSTRUCTION IN THE PATH OF THE TRACTOR-TRAILER. TIRE MARKS AT THE SCENE SUGGEST THAT JOHN FINK TOOK EVASIVE ACTION BY BRAKING AND STEERING LEFT TO AVOID THE DEVELOPING HAZARDS.    THE TRACTOR-TRAILER WRECKED, COMING TO REST WITH THE TRAILER ACROSS BOTH LANES OF I-26 AT THE APPROACH TO A BRIDGE SPANNING RR TRACKS BELOW. THE TRACTOR WAS SLIGHTLY OFF THE ROADWAY TO THE LEFT.    V1 INCURRED DAMAGE AND WAS STOPPED ABOUT 1/4 MILE FURTHER DOWN THE INTERSTATE (BEYOND THE BRIDGE DECK). V2 ALSO WRECKED. ITS FINAL POSITION WAS BETWEEN THE TRAILER AND THE BRIDGE DECK.    EITHER DURING THE COLLISION(S) DESCRIBED ABOVE OR THEIR IMMEDIATE AFTERMATH, THE CARGO ON V3 WAS IGNITED. V2 AND V3 WERE COMPLETELY CONSUMED BY FIRE. ONE OCCUPANT OF V2 AND TWO OCCUPANTS OF V3 WERE KILLED-EITHER BY THE WRECK OR BY THE FIRE.  ANOTHER OCCUPANT OF V2 WAS SEVERLY BURNED. V1 WAS DAMAGED FROM THE DRIVER'S SIDE DOOR THROUGH TO AND INCLUDING THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THERE WAS ONE OCCUPANT OF V1 AND HE WAS UNINJURED. A FOURTH VEHICLE, FOLLOWING V2 AND V3, DID NOT PLAY A ROLE IN THE ACCIDENT BUT WAS DESTROYED BY THE FIRE.  ITS OCCUPANTS WERE DESCRIBED AS UNINJURED.    EMERGENCY RESPONDERS EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE AND RECOVERED THE BODIES. INVESTIGATORS THEN COLLECTED DATA FROM THE SCENE. THIS TOOK SEVERAL HOURS. BY MID-AFTERNOON, THE WRECKAGE WAS ALLOWED TO BE REMOVED FROM THE SITE. PAVEMENT IMPROVEMENTS WERE DONE LATER THAT EVENING. SOIL REMEDIATION IN THE MEDIAN AREA WAS PERFORMED THE FOLLOWING DAY. UPON COMPLETION OF THE REMEDIATION WORK, THE WB LANES WERE OPENED.
column169: AT THIS TIME, IT APPEARS THAT THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS A VICTIM OF POOR DECISIONS AND ACTIONS BY OTHERS. IT IS BELIEVED THAT HE WAS DRIVING AT OR BELOW THE SPEED LIMIT. HE APPEARS TO HAVE ALSO MOVED (OR WAS MOVING) HIS TRUCK INTO THE LEFT LANE TO GIVE ADDITIONAL SPACE TO V1 AND V2.  ONCE IN THE LEFT LANE, HIS FOLLOWING DISTANCE WOULD HAVE BEEN A NON-FACTOR SINCE THERE WERE NO KNOWN OTHER VEHICLES IN THE LEFT LANE.  RECORDS FROM HIS COMPANY PHONE INDICATE THAT HE WAS NOT TALKING (VIA BLUE-TOOTH DEVICE) OR TEXTING AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. THERE ARE NO KNOWN TRUCK MAINTENANCE ISSUES THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THIS INCIDENT.    THE PRELIMINARY THEORY OF THE CAUSE OF THIS ACCIDENT SUGGESTS THAT V1 MAY HAVE ATTEMPTED TO MERGE INTO OCCUPIED SPACE ON THE INTERSTATE.  THIS ALLEGED ILL-ADVISED MANEUVER THEN CAUSED OTHER EVENTS THAT ULTIMATELY KILLED THREE PEOPLE AND SERIOUSLY INJURED ANOTHER.    THE SITE OF THE ACCIDENT IS CONCERNING.  THE WB ON-RAMP STARTS AT A POINT ABOVE THE GRADE OF THE INTERSTATE AND MERGES AFTER A SHORT AT-GRADE DISTANCE ONTO THE I-26 TRAVEL LANES.  LANDSCAPING OBSTRUCTS THE VIEW OF INTERSTATE TRAFFIC BY MERGING MOTORISTS AND VISE VERSA.  THE SHORT ACCELERATION LANE TAPERS TO NOTHING AT A NARROW BRIDGE (THE BRIDGE HAS TWO STANDARD-WIDTH TRAVEL LANES, BUT LITTLE OR NO SHOULDER WIDTH).  THIS CONFIGURATION MEANS THAT A VEHICLE ENTERING THE INTERSTATE MUST DEVELOP A HIGH RATE OF SPEED BY THE TIME IT IS IN A POSITION TO DECIDE WHERE IT WILL MERGE INTO INTERSTATE TRAFFIC.  THE ENTERING VEHICLE MAY NEED TO ACCELERATE FURTHER OR DECELERATE ABRUPTLY TO AVOID INTERSTATE TRAFFIC THAT COULD BE OCCUPYING DESIRABLE SPACE IN THE RIGHT TRAVEL LANE. IF THERE IS HESITATION TO MODIFY A DECISION TO MERGE OR BOTH VEHICLE ACCELERATE AND DECELERATE IN UNISON IN ORDER TO TRY TO CREATE SPACE ON THE INTERSTATE, THE MERGING VEHICLE WILL RUN OUT OF ACCELERATION LANE SPACE AND HIT THE BRIDGE. AS AN ALTERNATIVE TO HITTING THE BRIDGE, A MERGING MOTORIST MAY FEEL COMPELLED TO FORCE HIS/HER WAY ONTO THE INTERSTATE DESPITE THE PRESENCE OF ANOTHER VEHICLE. THIS ACTION COULD CAUSE THE DESTRUCTION EXPERIENCED IN THIS EVENT.    THEREFORE, I WOULD RECOMMEND THAT THE WB ACCELERATION LANE AT THIS INTERCHANGE BE LENGTHENED THROUGH THE LENGTH OF THE BRIDGE TO GIVE MERGING MOTORISTS MORE OPPORTUNITY TO MERGE SAFELY INTO INTERSTATE TRAFFIC. I WOULD ALSO SUPPORT ADDITIONAL AWARENESS TRAINING TO OTHER TRACTOR TRAILER DRIVERS ON ANY SUBJECT THAT JOHN FINK'S DRIVING IS FOUND TO BE DEFICIENT.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER JOHN FINK WAS TRAVELING WB ON I-26 NEAR MM 17 IN SOUTH CAROLINA AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30AM ON JUNE 26, 2015. HE HAD FINISHED LOADING HIS TRUCK WITH GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL ABOUT 15-20 MINUTES EARLIER AT THE KINDER MORGAN TERMINAL IN SPARTANBURG, SC.    JOHN IS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN FOLLOWING (NOT NECESSARILY IN THE SAME LANE) AN SUV (LABLED AS V2 IN THE ATTACHED DIAGRAM) AS HIS TRACTOR-TRAILER APPROACHED THE WB ON-RAMP OF THE INTERCHANGE AT MM 17. ANOTHER SUV (LABELED AS V1 IN TEH ATTACHED DIAGRAM) IS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN TRAVELING ON THE WB ON-RAMP AT THIS TIME, PREPARING TO ENTER THE INTERSTATE ROADWAY.    THE INITIAL THEORY PUT FORTH BY THE HP AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT SUGGESTED THAT V1 AND V2 INTERFERED WITH ONE ANOTHER AS V1 ATTEMPTED TO ENTER THE ROADWAY.  THE INTERFERENCE MAY HAVE BEEN A COLLISION BETWEEN V1 AND V2, OR SEVERE SWERVING OR BRAKING BY EITHER VEHICLE. THE THEORY CONTINUES THAT THE INTERACTION BETWEEN V1 AND V2 RESULTED IN EITHER A COLLISION THAT AFFECTED THE TRACTOR-TRAILER (V3) DIRECTLY OR CREATED AND INSTANTANEOUS OBSTRUCTION IN THE PATH OF THE TRACTOR-TRAILER. TIRE MARKS AT THE SCENE SUGGEST THAT JOHN FINK TOOK EVASIVE ACTION BY BRAKING AND STEERING LEFT TO AVOID THE DEVELOPING HAZARDS.    THE TRACTOR-TRAILER WRECKED, COMING TO REST WITH THE TRAILER ACROSS BOTH LANES OF I-26 AT THE APPROACH TO A BRIDGE SPANNING RR TRACKS BELOW. THE TRACTOR WAS SLIGHTLY OFF THE ROADWAY TO THE LEFT.    V1 INCURRED DAMAGE AND WAS STOPPED ABOUT 1/4 MILE FURTHER DOWN THE INTERSTATE (BEYOND THE BRIDGE DECK). V2 ALSO WRECKED. ITS FINAL POSITION WAS BETWEEN THE TRAILER AND THE BRIDGE DECK. column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Norfolk Southern personnel found tank car GATX90952 leaking during a coupling operation.  During this operation, a Norfolk Southern employee had potassium hydroxide from the tank car splashed on their arm.  Upon inspection by a contractor,  the leak was found to be coming from the relief valve.  The relief valve was found with loose bolts on the relief valve mounting flange.  The contractor (HEPACO) tightened the bolts to stop the leak.  The shipper submitted an OTMA to the FRA to move the car to destination for off-loading.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Tank car GATX 14639 was reported to be leaking by UPRR yard personnel.  Inspection of the car found the vapor valve open.  The valve was closed, stopping the release.  The top and side of the car were remediated and no further action was needed.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
